6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Formal vs.
 Informal Communication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To ensure accountability,
 Information Operations shall distinguish strictly between binding and non-binding communications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Formal Communications (Binding)
\series default
:
 Any written or recorded communication that creates an official record,
 authorizes work,
 directs action,
 commits funds,
 establishes scope,
 or signifies a decision.
 Examples include emails,
 memos,
 tickets/work orders,
 approved meeting minutes,
 status reports,
 and presentations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Informal Communications (Non-Binding)
\series default
:
 Verbal conversations,
 hallway discussions,
 or non-recorded phone calls.
 Informal communications do not authorize work,
 financial commitments,
 security-impacting changes,
 or policy deviations unless confirmed in writing through formal channels;
 however,
 personnel shall comply with lawful supervisory direction and shall request written confirmation within 
\series bold
one (1) business day
\series default
 of receiving an instruction requiring confirmation.
 If the instruction involves directives,
 financial commitments,
 procurement direction,
 scope changes,
 or architectural decisions,
 written confirmation shall be provided within 
\series bold
four (4) business hours
\series default
 in accordance with the Written Confirmation Rule.
 The issuing authority shall provide written confirmation within the applicable timeframe or the matter shall be escalated through the chain of command in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Written Confirmation Rule
\series default
:
 Verbal communications involving directives,
 financial commitments,
 procurement direction,
 scope changes,
 or architectural decisions shall be documented in writing within 
\series bold
four (4) business hours
\series default
 of the verbal communication.
 Verbal directives not reduced to writing within this window are presumptively void.
 Until written confirmation exists,
 the communication shall be treated as non-binding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Liability
\series default
:
 Personnel who act on verbal financial or procurement directives that lack written confirmation do so at personal and professional risk.
 Such actions may constitute a policy violation under Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Strategic Reporting Cadence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall maintain a predictable reporting rhythm to ensure leadership visibility and alignment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Monthly Executive Report
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall provide a formal written report to the County Manager covering project status,
 service performance (KPIs),
 budget variance,
 and emerging risks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Monthly Briefing
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall conduct an in-person status briefing with the County Manager to review the Monthly Executive Report and align priorities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Operational Communication Standards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Information Operations shall maintain a "No Surprise" standard regarding service availability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Scheduled Maintenance
\series default
:
 Planned maintenance affecting other departments shall be communicated at least 
\series bold
forty-eight (48) hours
\series default
 in advance whenever feasible.
 If forty-eight (48) hours is not feasible,
 notice shall be issued immediately upon scheduling and the exception shall be documented with justification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Unplanned Outages
\series default
:
 The Service Desk shall issue an initial stakeholder notification within 
\series bold
fifteen (15) minutes
\series default
 of confirming a widespread outage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Root Cause Analysis (RCA)
\series default
:
 Significant outages shall have a formal RCA provided to affected Department leadership within 
\series bold
five (5) business days
\series default
 of resolution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Crisis and Incident Communication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
During a major cybersecurity incident or infrastructure crisis,
 strict information discipline is mandatory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
One Voice Rule (Strategic/Public)
\series default
:
 The IT Director (or designated Incident Commander) shall serve as the sole authoritative source for strategic and public-facing messaging.
 Personnel shall not speculate in writing on cause,
 attribution,
 or scope until authorized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Technical Coordination
\series default
:
 The One Voice Rule shall not prohibit technical staff from communicating operational details to vendors,
 service providers,
 or partners when necessary to resolve an incident,
 provided communications are limited to technical scope and follow data handling requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Incident Communications
\series default
:
 Incident communications shall follow 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 CJIS-related incidents shall follow CJIS reporting requirements and 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

/
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 procedures,
 including the one (1) hour reporting requirement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Public and Stakeholder Notification
\series default
:
 Notifications to the public and stakeholders regarding security breaches shall be executed in strict accordance with the 'most expedient time possible' standard mandated by 
\series bold
NRS 603A.220
\series default
 and the reporting windows defined in CJIS Security Policy 5.3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJIS Reporting
\series default
:
 Personnel shall report suspected or confirmed security incidents immediately,
 but not to exceed one (1) hour after discovery.
 If confirmed,
 the IT Director (LASO) shall notify the CSO,
 SIB Chief,
 or Interface Agency Official per CJIS IR-6(b).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Legal Review
\series default
:
 When directed by County legal counsel,
 incident-related written communications shall be routed through the District Attorney’s Office to support legal review and appropriate handling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Information Exchange Agreements (IEAs)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Requirement
\series default
:
 Any arrangement that enables external access to,
 transmission of,
 or exchange of Criminal Justice Information (CJI) shall be supported by a written Information Exchange Agreement (IEA) or equivalent contract language,
 consistent with CJIS Policy Area 1 requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Agreement Content
\series default
:
 Information exchange documentation shall define:
 (a) interface characteristics;
 (b) security controls implemented at each connection point;
 (c) authorized data elements;
 (d) restrictions on connections;
 and (e) terms/termination conditions,
 consistent with NIST CA-3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Custody
\series default
:
 Executed Information Exchange Agreements shall be stored in the County’s designated contract repository with version control and shall be retrievable within one (1) business day upon request.
\end_layout

